 also includes pieces by politicians and foreign diplomats; by literary giants Octavio Paz, Gloria Anzaldúa, and Carlos Fuentes; and by and about revolutionary leaders Pancho Villa and Emiliano Zapata. This revised and updated edition features new selections that address twenty-first-century developments, including the rise of narcopolitics, the economic and personal costs of the United States’ mass deportation programs, the political activism of indigenous healers and manufacturing workers, and the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic. The Mexico Reader is an essential resource for travelers, students, and experts alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh1 aAguirre Beltrán, Gonzalo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlamán, Lucas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlfaro Siqueiros, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnzaldúa, Gloria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnold, Channing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtristain, Miguel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBacon, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenítez, Fernando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonfil Batalla, Guillermo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBustamante Agudelo, Andrés, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCabrera, Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalderón de la Barca, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalles, Plutarco Elías, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r